---
import Layout from '../../../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Repl from '../../../../components/Repl';
import SchemeRepl from '../../../../components/SchemeRepl';
import Neighbors from "../../../../components/Neighbors.astro";
import PrevNext from "../../../../components/PrevNext.astro";
---

<Layout title="Econ Ch.16 — Inflation" favicon="💰">
  <main>

    <a href="/reading/economics/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">← back to economics</a>

    <h1>Inflation</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Irving Fisher · 1911 / Milton Friedman · 1963 · <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inflation"><img src="/reading/wikipedia.svg" alt="wp" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>Wikipedia: Inflation</a></p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none"><strong>Inflation</strong> is a sustained increase in the general price level. The quantity theory of money (MV = PQ) says prices rise when money supply grows faster than output. Demand-pull inflation comes from too much spending. Cost-push comes from rising input costs. The Fisher effect links nominal interest rates to inflation expectations.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- 1. Quantity theory -->
    <h3>Quantity theory of money: MV = PQ</h3>
    <p>The equation of exchange: Money supply (M) times velocity (V, how often each dollar is spent) equals the price level (P) times real output (Q). If V and Q are roughly constant, then increasing M proportionally increases P. "Inflation is always and everywhere a monetary phenomenon" (Friedman).</p>

    <!-- SVG: Price level rising as money supply expands -->
    <div class="flex justify-center my-6">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 400 280" class="w-full max-w-md" style="font-family: ui-monospace, monospace;">
        <!-- Axes -->
        <line x1="60" y1="240" x2="380" y2="240" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" opacity="0.5"/>
        <line x1="60" y1="240" x2="60" y2="30" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" opacity="0.5"/>
        <text x="220" y="270" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="12" fill-opacity="0.5">Time</text>
        <text x="25" y="135" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="12" fill-opacity="0.5" transform="rotate(-90, 25, 135)">Level</text>

        <!-- Money supply line (rising steeply) -->
        <polyline points="80,200 140,180 200,150 260,110 320,60" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" opacity="0.6"/>
        <text x="335" y="55" fill="currentColor" font-size="11" fill-opacity="0.5">M (money)</text>

        <!-- Price level line (follows with lag) -->
        <polyline points="80,200 140,195 200,170 260,135 320,85" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-dasharray="5,3" opacity="0.6"/>
        <text x="335" y="80" fill="currentColor" font-size="11" fill-opacity="0.5">P (prices)</text>

        <!-- Real output (roughly flat) -->
        <polyline points="80,200 140,195 200,192 260,188 320,185" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="2,4" opacity="0.4"/>
        <text x="335" y="182" fill="currentColor" font-size="11" fill-opacity="0.4">Q (output)</text>

        <!-- Gap annotation -->
        <line x1="260" y1="110" x2="260" y2="135" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="2,2" opacity="0.3"/>
        <text x="280" y="128" fill="currentColor" font-size="9" fill-opacity="0.4">lag</text>

        <!-- MV = PQ label -->
        <text x="200" y="250" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="11" fill-opacity="0.4">MV = PQ: more money chasing same goods = higher prices</text>
      </svg>
    </div>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Quantity theory of money: MV = PQ
; If V and Q constant, doubling M doubles P

(define V 5)   ; velocity (constant)
(define Q 100) ; real output (constant)

(define (price-level M) (/ (* M V) Q))

(display "MV = PQ, with V=5, Q=100") (newline) (newline)

(for-each
  (lambda (M)
    (display "  M=$") (display M)
    (display " -> P=") (display (exact->inexact (price-level M)))
    (newline))
  '(100 200 400 800 1600))

(newline)
(display "Double the money, double the prices.")
(newline)
(display "Real output unchanged. Only prices adjust.")
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Quantity theory: MV = PQ
V = 5   # velocity
Q = 100 # real output

for M in [100, 200, 400, 800, 1600]:
    P = (M * V) / Q
    print("M=$" + str(M) + " -> P=" + str(round(P, 1)))

print("")
print("Double M => double P (with V, Q constant)")
`} />
    </div>


    <!-- 2. Demand-pull vs cost-push -->
    <h3>Demand-pull vs cost-push</h3>
    <p><strong>Demand-pull</strong>: too much money chasing too few goods. Government stimulus, credit expansion, or consumer confidence boosts spending beyond capacity. <strong>Cost-push</strong>: rising input costs (oil shocks, wage spirals) force firms to raise prices even without excess demand. Both produce inflation, but the policy response differs.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Demand-pull: excess spending raises prices
; Cost-push: rising costs raise prices

(define capacity 100)

; Demand-pull scenario
(define (demand-pull-price spending)
  (if (> spending capacity)
      (+ 1.0 (* 0.02 (- spending capacity)))  ; prices rise
      1.0))

(display "Demand-pull inflation:") (newline)
(for-each
  (lambda (s)
    (display "  Spending=") (display s)
    (display ", Price level=")
    (display (exact->inexact (demand-pull-price s)))
    (newline))
  '(80 100 110 120 150))

(newline)

; Cost-push scenario
(define base-cost 10)
(define markup 1.3)

(define (cost-push-price input-cost)
  (* input-cost markup))

(display "Cost-push inflation (30% markup):") (newline)
(for-each
  (lambda (c)
    (display "  Input cost=$") (display c)
    (display ", Price=$")
    (display (exact->inexact (cost-push-price c)))
    (newline))
  '(10 12 15 20 30))
`} />


    <!-- 3. Fisher effect -->
    <h3>Fisher effect</h3>
    <p>Irving Fisher's insight: the nominal interest rate equals the real interest rate plus expected inflation. If inflation is expected to be 5%, lenders demand 5% more to preserve real returns. The real rate is set by the supply and demand for loanable funds; the nominal rate adjusts one-for-one with inflation expectations.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Fisher equation: i = r + expected inflation
; i = nominal rate, r = real rate

(define real-rate 0.03)  ; 3% real

(display "Fisher effect: nominal = real + expected inflation")
(newline) (newline)

(for-each
  (lambda (pi)
    (let ((nominal (+ real-rate pi)))
      (display "  Expected inflation=")
      (display (exact->inexact (* pi 100))) (display "%")
      (display " -> Nominal rate=")
      (display (exact->inexact (* nominal 100))) (display "%")
      (newline)))
  '(0.0 0.02 0.05 0.10 0.20))

(newline)
(display "Real purchasing power preserved regardless of inflation")
(newline)
(display "(if expectations are correct)")
`} />


    <!-- 4. Hyperinflation -->
    <h3>Hyperinflation</h3>
    <p>When governments print money to cover deficits, inflation can spiral. Velocity increases as people spend money immediately, reinforcing the price rise. Historical examples: Weimar Germany (1923, prices doubled every few days), Zimbabwe (2008, monthly inflation of 79.6 billion percent), Venezuela (2018, annual rate above one million percent).</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Hyperinflation: compounding monthly inflation

(define (hyperinflate monthly-rate months)
  (let loop ((m 0) (price 1.0))
    (if (= m months) price
        (loop (+ m 1) (* price (+ 1 monthly-rate))))))

(display "Starting price: $1.00") (newline) (newline)

; Moderate: 2% monthly
(display "2% monthly (moderate):") (newline)
(display "  After 12 months: $")
(display (exact->inexact (hyperinflate 0.02 12))) (newline)

; High: 50% monthly (Cagan's threshold for hyperinflation)
(display "50% monthly (hyperinflation):") (newline)
(display "  After 12 months: $")
(display (exact->inexact (hyperinflate 0.50 12))) (newline)

; Extreme: 300% monthly (Zimbabwe-like)
(display "300% monthly (extreme):") (newline)
(display "  After 12 months: $")
(display (exact->inexact (hyperinflate 3.00 12))) (newline)

(display "Hyperinflation destroys money as a store of value")
`} />


    <!-- Key concepts -->
    <h3>Key concepts</h3>
    <div class="overflow-x-auto">
      <table class="w-full text-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-700">
            <th class="py-2 pr-4 text-left">Concept</th>
            <th class="py-2 text-left">Definition</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800"><td class="py-2 pr-4">MV = PQ</td><td>Money times velocity equals price times output</td></tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800"><td class="py-2 pr-4">Demand-pull</td><td>Inflation from excess aggregate demand</td></tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800"><td class="py-2 pr-4">Cost-push</td><td>Inflation from rising production costs</td></tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800"><td class="py-2 pr-4">Fisher effect</td><td>Nominal rate = real rate + expected inflation</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="py-2 pr-4">Hyperinflation</td><td>Monthly inflation exceeding 50% (Cagan's definition)</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>


